'''Ed Olle''' was a [[college baseball]] and [[college basketball]] player, a men's college basketball [[head coach]], and an [[athletics director]] at [[The University of Texas at Austin]]. Olle played for [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball]] head coach [[E. J. Stewart|E. J. "Doc" Stewart]] and for [[Texas Longhorns baseball|Texas baseball]] head coach [[Billy Disch|William J. "Billy" Disch]]. He received all-[[Southwest Conference]] honors in baseball in 1926 and 1927.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texassports.com/sports/2014/5/20/BB_0520144803.aspx?id=534 | format= | title=Baseball Conference Honors | work=texassports.com | accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> Olle would go on to coach the Longhorns in basketball for three seasons (1931<U+2013>34) following the departure of [[Mysterious Walker|"Mysterious" Fred Walker]] in 1931.<ref name="2014-15 Texas Basketball Fact Book">{{Cite web|url=http://texassports_com.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/2014/11/12/2014_15_Texas_Basketball_Fact_Book.pdf | format=PDF | title=2014-15 Texas Basketball Fact Book | work=texassports.com | page=65<U+2013>66 |accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> His 1932<U+2013>33 team finished the season as Southwest Conference champions with a 22<U+2013>1 overall record and would many decades later receive retroactive recognition as that season's national champion in the [[Premo-Porretta Power Poll]] (the team playing as it did in an era preceding the existence of national basketball tournaments or polling).<ref name="2014-15 Texas Basketball Fact Book" /><ref>{{cite book|title=ESPN College Basketball Encyclopedia: The Complete History of the Men's Game|editor-last=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Books|location=New York, NY|year=2009|page=543|ISBN=978-0-345-51392-2}}</ref> After three seasons as head coach, Olle resigned and moved into a position in the UT Athletics Department, first under [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas football]] head coach and Athletics Director [[Jack Chevigny]], and later under football coach and Athletics Director [[Dana X. Bible]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Longhorn Hoops: The History of Texas Basketball|author=Pennington, Richard|publisher=Athletic Department, The University of Texas at Austin|location=Austin, TX|year=1998|page=47|ISBN=978-0-292-76585-6}}</ref> He was subsequently hired as UT Athletics Director in 1956 and remained in that position until 1962.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Darrell Royal Named Texas Football Coach | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | publisher=Tribune Publishing | date=December 19, 1956 |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1956/12/19/page/51/article/darrell-royal-named-texas-football-coach | accessdate=May 3, 2005}}</ref>

